reviewText: Ok, I am not a Daddy Yankee fan (though he is very cute) but I still desired to see this film, as I try to catch as many films made for Puerto Rican cinema as possible. The movie was much better than expected. Its main character, Daddy Yankee, portrays Dinero a head drug dealer in a caserio. Dinero is a thug (to the full sense of the word) with heart (not unlike some young kids who get sucked into the world of easy money.) Dinero is loyal and is thus surrounded by many loyal friends but he offers a job to one who will become his, and his squads traitor- this is where the drama ensues and becomes beyond negative, violence begetting violence. In the mix of all of this- is Dinero's plan to get out of the street way of life- Reggaeton.Overall, I would say that this is a good film, though intertwined with alot of negativity and a little too much ghettoness (real word?.)
summary: This is the type of film that shows heart in those lost souls portrayed within

reviewText: Daddy Yankee is widely known around the world. And this film reveals the origin of many of his repertoire as self confessional statements.Valle Verde is the neighborhood where he lives and grows up: A relentless and violent jungle in which only the strong survive. He is the chief commander of a team that deals with pills. In the middle of this messy environment, the prize of a life is worthless. But as the time goes by, a close friend realizes about his natural talent, and finally persuades him to make a record that eventually will become him the exit to leave this bloody hell.A balanced script without extreme doses of sentimentalism or self compassion. Specially recommended for Yankee's fans.
summary: Music was his redemption and his bliss!

reviewText: I am a new Daddy Yankee fan, so when I found out about this movie I purchased it. My co-workers and I watched this movie and we loved it. In fact we had a ritual where we would watch it at least once a month. I thought the acting was good, DY was gorgeous, as always, and we were able to see a side of Puerto Rico that is not normally seen. However, I would have liked the film to go more in depth as far as his relationship with the young lady, and maybe a little more backgroud on his character, Edgar Dinero. All in all it was an enjoyable film. I liked the interviews at the end of the film also. If you are a DY fan, I would most definately recommend that you get this film!
